· 17. clava: this has reference to cylindrical pieces oi wood possessed by the ephors, and carried by all generals on expedi· tions. 'lt was usual ior the ephors to wind a narrow strip oi leather slantwise around the wooden cylinder, and then to write short secret dispatches lengthwise upon theleather. When the leather was unrolled‚ merely a series oi single letters appeared, having no consecutive meaning. The officer receiving it would wind it about a precisely similar cylinder‚ thus learning its con· tents. The cylinder and the message could each be called scytale, oi which clava staff is a literal translation 3 in the present instance the strip oi leather written upon is meant, so use scytale in trans- lating.
